Here's another elementary proof (which also works for general Banach algebras and nontheless avoids complex analysis) based on  Rickart's proof of the Gelfand formula    *First things first: the limit of  $\|A^n\|^{1/n}$  exists by virtue of the subadditivityof the sequence  $a_n=\log(\|A^n\|^{1/n})$  and Fekete's lemma. The limit equals  $\inf_{n\in \mathbb{N}}\|A^n\|^{1/n}$    *Next, it is easy to see that  $ho(A) \leq 
u:=\lim_{n 	o \infty}\|A^n\|^{1/n}$ . In the matrix-case, just act with  $A^n$  on the leading eigenvector and see what happens in order to arrive at this conclusion.    *So we still have to prove that  $
u \leq ho(A)$ .     First suppose that  $
u=0$ . I will show that  $0$  must be an eigenvalue then, which suffices for our proof in this case. If  $0$  were not an eigenvalue of  $A$ , then  $A$  is invertible and taking the norm of  $I=A^n (A^{-1})^n$  yields  $1 \leq \|A^n\|^{1/n} \|(A^{-1})^n\|^{1/n} \leq \|A^n\|^{1/n}\|A^{-1}\|	o 
u \|A^{-1}\|$  which results in a contradiction against the assumption  $
u=0$ .    From now on suppose that  $
u>0$ . Assume that  $ho(A)<
u$  (anticipating a contradiction). The following identity, which holds for any  $q>ho(A)$ , will come in handy,  $$\left( rac{A^n}{q^n}-Iight)^{-1}= rac{1}{n}\sum_{j=0}^{n-1} \left( rac{A}{\omega_n^jq}-Iight)^{-1}\qquad (1)$$  where  $\omega_n\in \mathbb{C}$  is a primitive n'th root of unity. This identity can be verified by multiplying both sides by  $ rac{A^n}{q^n}-I= rac{A^n}{(\omega_n^j q)^n}-I$ . Fix  $\varepsilon>0$  (we will later send it to 0). By our assumption that  $ho(A) <
u$ , both  $
u$  and  $
u_\varepsilon:= rac{
u}{1-\varepsilon}$  can substitute  $q$  in the identity (1). Hence  $$\left\|\left( rac{A^n}{
u_\varepsilon^n}-Iight)^{-1}-\left( rac{A^n}{
u^n}-Iight)^{-1}ight\| \leq  rac{1}{n}\sum_{j=0}^{n-1} \left\|\left( rac{A}{\omega_n^j
u_\varepsilon}-Iight)^{-1}-\left( rac{A}{\omega_n^j
u}-Iight)^{-1}ight\|$$   $$= rac{1}{n}\sum_{j=0}^{n-1}|
u_\varepsilon^{-1}-
u^{-1}|\left\|\left( rac{A}{\omega_n^j
u_\varepsilon}-Iight)^{-1}A\left( rac{A}{\omega_n^j
u}-Iight)^{-1}ight\|$$   $$\leq  rac{\varepsilon}{n
u}\sum_{j=0}^{n-1}\left\|\left( rac{A}{\omega_n^j
u_\varepsilon}-Iight)^{-1}ight\|\|A\|\left\|\left( rac{A}{\omega_n^j
u}-Iight)^{-1}ight\|$$  where I used a variant of the resolvent identity in the step in the middle. The key now is to find an  $M>0$  which bounds the individual terms in the final sum from above. To find  M  one establishes the continuity of the map  $\varphi: A\subset \mathbb{C} 	o M^{m 	imes m}: z \mapsto \left( rac{A}{z}-Iight)^{-1}$  where  $A$  is the (compact) annulus  $\{z \in \mathbb{C}:\,
u\leq |z|\leq 2
u\}$  (easy and therefore omitted). Compactness of  $A$  means that  $\|\varphi\|$  reaches a maximum  $N<+\infty$ . Wrapping everything together, we then find  $$\left\|\left( rac{A^n}{
u_\varepsilon^n}-Iight)^{-1}-\left( rac{A^n}{
u^n}-Iight)^{-1}ight\| \leq  rac{\varepsilon N^2 \|A\|}{
u} = C \varepsilon\qquad (2)$$  where it is important that  $C$  does not depend on  n . Letting  $n 	o \infty$ , we have  $ rac{\|A^n\|^{1/n}}{
u_{\varepsilon}} 	o 1-\varepsilon$  and therefore  $ rac{\|A^n\|}{
u_{\varepsilon}^n} 	o 0$  and therefore  $ rac{A^n}{
u_{\varepsilon}^n} 	o 0$  and therefore  $\left( rac{A^n}{
u^n}-Iight)^{-1} 	o -I$  and therefore (since the right hand side of (2) can be made arbitrarily small) necessarily  $\left( rac{A^n}{
u^n}-Iight)^{-1}	o -I+O(\varepsilon)$  which requires that  $ rac{A^n}{
u^n}=O(\varepsilon)$ . But that is impossible since  $
u=\inf_{n\in \mathbb{N}}\|A^n\|^{1/n}$ . So we arrive at the anticipated contradiction.
